-GIT is a distributed version control system (DVCS)
it was created by Linus Torvald (creator of the Linux kernel)

-Each change of your code (git commit) can be captured and tracked throughout the history of your project (git tree, or, git log --oneline)


# Common GIT terms

-commit:
represents a change of data in the local git repository

-tree:
represent the entire history of a repo

-remote:
a version of your project hosted elsewhere, used for exchanging commits

-branches:
divergents paths from your main branch of development, allowing for isolated changes (branches with their own history and commits)

-clone:
creates a complete local copy of a repository, including its history

-checkout:
the ability to switch between different branches or commits in your repo

-pull:
downloads changes from a remote repo and merges them into your branch

-push:
uploads your local repo changes to a remote repo

-fetch:
downloads data from a remote repo without integrating it into your work

-reset:
undoes local changes, with options to unstage or revert commits

-merge:
combines multiple commit histories into one

-staging files:
prepares and organizes changes for the following commit (git commit -m)

